This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for type identity and coercion.

## Semantic identity

A type checker needs identities that survive beyond source spelling.

- Each module owns local `TypeId` handles.
- Cross-module interfaces use canonical identities.
- Aliases change spelling, not identity.
- Fixed collection capacity is part of type identity.
- Maps are their own constructed type shape.
- Unknown external parameters use an explicit unknown state rather than fake IDs.

## Coercion

Expression checking determines a natural type.

Contextual coercion is applied only by an explicit receiving boundary such as a declaration, assignment, return, parameter, field or typed collection entry.

Access mode is not type identity. `~` describes exclusive access at a boundary rather than a separate runtime type.

## Rewrite focus

Explain nominal versus constructed types, local handles, canonical identity, contextual typing and the difference between coercion and explicit cast.

Canonical details live in `docs/compiler-design-overview.md`.
